WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.360
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee.

00:06.360 --> 00:10.760
Just before I came into the studio, I heard some very good news for the people in the Tennessee

00:10.760 --> 00:14.560
Valley area, and I want to tell you about it now.

00:14.560 --> 00:19.840
The good news is that the Senate Public Works Committee has finally reported out a self-financing

00:19.840 --> 00:23.480
bill for the Tennessee Valley Authority.

00:23.480 --> 00:28.520
We all know that it's necessary for the TVA to build more steam plants and hydroelectric

00:28.520 --> 00:34.800
facilities to be able to furnish the increasing demand for power for electricity and the Tennessee

00:34.800 --> 00:35.800
Valley.

00:35.800 --> 00:39.760
While we haven't been able to get any appropriations for it for a long time, so this

00:39.760 --> 00:46.680
bill is to enable the TVA to issue a revenue bond with the users of power to pay back through

00:46.680 --> 00:49.880
the TVA over a course of years.

00:49.880 --> 00:53.600
The bill has been tied up for some time, but it's been finally reported.

00:54.160 --> 00:59.840
Of course, some compromises had to be made, and there was a giving and taking on both sides,

00:59.840 --> 01:04.200
but I think the bill that has finally been brought out is a good compromise.

01:04.200 --> 01:10.600
It's one that the TVA can live with, and I get along under, and I think it's about the

01:10.600 --> 01:12.520
best it could be done.

01:12.520 --> 01:19.240
The compromise is that the bill is for a five-year period, enabling the TVA to issue $750

01:19.240 --> 01:22.360
million worth of bonds over a period of five years.

01:22.640 --> 01:27.720
After that, we review the program and then see what needs to be done.

01:27.720 --> 01:34.960
Another compromise is that the 40-year amortization program whereby the TVA has to repay back its

01:34.960 --> 01:40.200
original investment within 40 years has been taken out of the bill, and in lieu of that,

01:40.200 --> 01:45.920
the TVA will pay interest at the average rate which the government pays on the amount

01:45.920 --> 01:48.960
that has been appropriated to it.

01:48.960 --> 01:55.360
The committee got into a great deal of difficulty over the so-called limit on the area to be served

01:55.360 --> 01:56.360
at the TVA.

01:56.360 --> 02:02.360
And the compromise is that if the TVA area is extended in any substantial way, it can

02:02.360 --> 02:05.000
only be done by an act of funds.

02:05.000 --> 02:11.200
But if it's a small, minute extension to serve some REA-electrical office adjacent to

02:11.200 --> 02:17.680
the TVA area, that may be done provided the TVA notifies the Congress in which 60 days

02:17.680 --> 02:20.320
to be served whether there's any objection.

02:20.320 --> 02:25.160
Under the compromise bill, the Secretary of the Treasury can delay the issuance of bonds

02:25.160 --> 02:31.360
for 45 days in order to fit in with the government's overall fiscal focus.

02:31.360 --> 02:35.680
I want to congratulate Senator Robert Kerr of Oklahoma, the chief sponsor of this bill and

02:35.680 --> 02:41.680
the chairman of the Subcommittee, Alan Colleg, Senator Gore, who is a member of the committee

02:41.680 --> 02:47.360
of Senator Hill of Alabama, Senator Cooper of Kentucky, and many others who have worked

02:47.360 --> 02:50.280
on the bill very, very hard.

02:50.280 --> 02:53.080
The bill came out with two Republican votes.

02:53.080 --> 02:57.880
Let's show the sure that it wouldn't be classified as a partisan matter when it reaches the

02:57.880 --> 03:04.880
floor so that I hope that we can pass the bill with a big majority that will also give

03:04.880 --> 03:08.800
it some impetus to get through the House of Representatives.

03:08.800 --> 03:12.240
We're working on a deadline in connection with this bill.

03:12.240 --> 03:17.760
We cannot be considered this week under the rules of the Senate, and we are going to

03:17.760 --> 03:24.520
try very hard to get it up early next week before July 8th, the date on which the so-called

03:24.520 --> 03:29.000
civil rights long debate of Philobuster will take place.

03:29.000 --> 03:35.960
We have spoken to the majority leader and to others in this effort, and I am very, very

03:35.960 --> 03:38.640
hopeful that this can be done.

03:38.640 --> 03:44.440
Well, that's the first bit of good news we've had insofar as TVA legislation for some time

03:44.440 --> 03:45.440
to be concerned.

03:45.440 --> 03:49.640
I didn't want to talk with you today about another important matter that happened in the

03:49.640 --> 03:51.760
Senate this week.

03:51.760 --> 04:00.280
We all remember the Hungarian revolt last fall, how the people rose up against the communist

04:00.280 --> 04:01.280
mess.

04:01.280 --> 04:05.360
We all wanted to do something about it that didn't know what to do.

04:05.360 --> 04:09.500
The United Nations had a committee that composed the five members of five nations which

04:09.500 --> 04:12.960
has randomly condemned what the communist did.

04:12.960 --> 04:18.380
And the United States Senate passed a resolution unanimously asking our delegate in the UN

04:18.380 --> 04:24.640
to urge the General Assembly to be called in order to take this matter up again.

04:24.640 --> 04:26.640
I hope that's going to be done.

04:26.640 --> 04:27.640
That's an idea.

04:27.640 --> 04:28.640
What's going on?

04:28.640 --> 04:34.840
Well, Dick Wallace, my administrative assistant, his head is the Keptish Derby, which is being

04:34.840 --> 04:37.160
held at Savannah Tennessee.

04:37.160 --> 04:40.920
This month I'm going down Saturday to be there at Derby.

04:40.920 --> 04:42.360
And I know I'm going to have a good time.

04:42.360 --> 04:47.680
We are mighty proud of our Tennessee blue cats, no fish are better.

04:47.680 --> 04:53.040
We are challenging Colorado deferring to shop to the senators and let them determine which

04:53.040 --> 04:54.040
will, which tastes better.

04:54.040 --> 04:57.040
And we know that Tennessee cats will win out.

04:57.040 --> 04:58.040
That's all for now.

04:58.040 --> 04:59.040
Thank you very much.

05:05.840 --> 05:13.760
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, as you know the anti-trust and monopoly subcommittee

05:13.760 --> 05:20.840
of which I am chairman has been conducting hearings and so-called administered prices,

05:20.840 --> 05:25.040
administered prices or those which do not react to what we ordinarily consider to be the

05:25.040 --> 05:28.400
competitive forces in our economy.

05:28.400 --> 05:31.200
Their prices set by decision of management.

05:31.200 --> 05:36.160
They may be raised when demand is falling, contrair to the ordinary views of inflation.

05:36.160 --> 05:40.600
Well, we've had a number of distinguished economists who have discussed this problem

05:40.600 --> 05:42.680
before our subcommittee.

05:42.680 --> 05:48.960
And right now we have Mr. Roger Blow, chairman of the board of the United States Steel Corporation,

05:48.960 --> 05:52.040
and a number of his fellow officers before it.

05:52.040 --> 05:56.720
Now all of these distinguished gentlemen have discussed in learned terms such things as

05:56.720 --> 06:00.280
administered prices as opposed to the free market.

06:00.280 --> 06:05.520
But sometimes you get the clearest explanation, the finest understanding of the differences

06:05.520 --> 06:09.560
between the two from unexpected sources.

06:09.560 --> 06:14.800
Ours came from a letter to the editor, but appeared in a little weekly paper down in

06:14.800 --> 06:17.680
weekly county at Dresden, Tennessee.

06:17.680 --> 06:19.960
It is signed simply J.A.

06:19.960 --> 06:24.320
I have no idea who J.A. is, although I'm curious.

06:24.320 --> 06:29.080
I read this letter across the committee table to Mr. Blow this week, and I'd like to read

06:29.080 --> 06:35.240
it to you because I think that in very simple and humorous terms, it explains the fight

06:35.240 --> 06:36.720
of our economy.

06:36.720 --> 06:38.720
This is the letter.

06:38.720 --> 06:43.920
Dear editor, the trouble with inflation is that not enough people understand its calling.

06:43.920 --> 06:50.080
Right at this point Mr. Blow interrupted and said, I agree with that 100% to 100%.

06:50.080 --> 06:54.840
But continuing the letter, I had noticed in a copy of a newspaper which a neighbor of

06:54.840 --> 07:01.560
mine brought a mere mess of fish in, or your information it wasn't a copy of your paper

07:01.560 --> 07:04.000
as this one had a fishy smell.

07:04.000 --> 07:09.720
That the price of steel had recently gone up $6 a ton, which clearly indicated that the

07:09.720 --> 07:13.920
steel industry has let its newspaper subscription expire.

07:13.920 --> 07:19.720
As President Eisenhower only the day before had asked business to hold prices down voluntarily.

07:19.720 --> 07:23.960
And as a result, a lot of other things were automatically going up.

07:23.960 --> 07:29.160
For example, naturally the watch manufacturers on hearing the price of steel had gone up

07:29.160 --> 07:32.680
will figure that they ought to go up on the price of their watches.

07:32.680 --> 07:37.360
As everybody knows the steel spring on the watches made of steel, even if it doesn't weigh

07:37.360 --> 07:39.200
over and out.

07:39.200 --> 07:45.440
Power points, tractors, cars, pickups, naturally will require an increase in prices to offset

07:45.440 --> 07:48.440
the rise in the price of steel.

07:48.440 --> 07:52.840
And so I decided that what was good for industry was good for me.

07:52.840 --> 07:58.960
Consequently, when I took a dozen eggs in the town yesterday to sell, I told the store

07:58.960 --> 08:02.280
I'd have to have five cents more for my eggs.

08:02.280 --> 08:05.000
How come the store owner asks?

08:05.000 --> 08:06.400
Don't you read your newspaper?

08:06.400 --> 08:10.280
It's on account of the increase in the price of steel, I explain.

08:10.280 --> 08:12.720
Now here's the rub.

08:12.720 --> 08:17.440
Instead of nodding his head in agreement and saying there didn't seem to be any way around

08:17.440 --> 08:19.440
if he does laugh.

08:19.440 --> 08:24.720
You could see he didn't have any full understanding of inflation and the upward price spiral.

08:24.720 --> 08:27.200
Don't believe I'd be interested, he said.

08:27.200 --> 08:31.560
But my cost are going up and I've got to have more money for these eggs.

08:31.560 --> 08:36.920
Don't believe I'd be interested, he said, and turned around and waited on another customer.

08:36.920 --> 08:42.000
Now I could have waited him out, but from long experience I knew the eggs couldn't.

08:42.000 --> 08:46.440
So I sold the eggs, sold the eggs at his price and came on home.

08:47.240 --> 08:52.040
It's the people who don't understand inflation that's causing this country so much trouble.

08:52.040 --> 08:55.760
I don't mind paying six dollars a ton more for steel.

08:55.760 --> 08:59.800
If somebody will recognize that I ought to get more from my eggs.

08:59.800 --> 09:04.800
There are more people than you realize who are out of tune with me and with my hymn.

09:04.800 --> 09:07.520
You're a spacefully J.A.

09:07.520 --> 09:08.920
And there you have it, my friends.

09:08.920 --> 09:15.040
A clear distinction between free and competitive market and the administered price market.

09:15.040 --> 09:19.560
And an explanation of why this inflation, which is our number one problem,

09:19.560 --> 09:25.960
is not a simple traditional kind that can easily be cured by any simple traditional remedy,

09:25.960 --> 09:28.160
such as the tight money policy.

09:28.160 --> 09:32.000
As a matter of fact, that policy doesn't do a thing to US steel,

09:32.000 --> 09:35.280
but it makes the egg business a whole lot rougher.

09:35.280 --> 09:39.040
But we'll have more to tell you about our fight against inflation

09:39.040 --> 09:43.480
for the judiciary subcommittee from time to time.

09:43.520 --> 09:46.120
In any event, we've got to do something about it.

09:46.120 --> 09:48.720
Thank you and goodbye until next week.

09:59.560 --> 10:02.560
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee.

10:02.560 --> 10:07.040
First on this program today, I would like to bring you up today as to the progress

10:07.040 --> 10:12.560
of being made in connection with the TBA self-financing bill, which is now pending in

10:12.560 --> 10:13.560
Congress.

10:13.560 --> 10:18.840
We will all recall that it's been almost five years since the TBA has had any appropriations

10:18.840 --> 10:23.960
for the building of a steam plant or for a hydroelectric facility.

10:23.960 --> 10:28.920
And that being denied appropriations is necessary for us to have a self-financing bill so that

10:28.920 --> 10:35.920
the TBA can issue its own bond, which it will repay from its own revenue, and which will

10:35.920 --> 10:40.720
only be revenue in that general government obligation bond.

10:40.720 --> 10:45.960
Along with Senator Gore and the Senators from the Tennessee Valley area, I'm a co-sponsored

10:45.960 --> 10:52.040
the so-called Kerr Bill, which would allow the Board of Directors and TBA to issue bonds

10:52.040 --> 10:59.200
and to be a responsible group and agency in connection with them and their repayment.

10:59.200 --> 11:01.720
Five bills are pending before the public works committee.

11:01.720 --> 11:04.840
We've been having quite a number of discussions about the matter.

11:04.840 --> 11:11.440
There's some parity that we got some bill out this year because it takes years to build

11:11.440 --> 11:17.240
steam plants, and we're not going to have power enough by the winter of 1959 unless we

11:17.240 --> 11:20.240
build some more.

11:20.240 --> 11:27.440
These conferences seem to be pulled out some hope that we can get a bill passed in the Senate

11:27.440 --> 11:32.880
and perhaps in the House and one that the President will not veto that the TBA can live

11:32.880 --> 11:33.880
by.

11:33.880 --> 11:37.560
But I think it's going to be necessary, and I personally believe that in order to get

11:37.560 --> 11:40.160
a bill passed, we'll have to make some concessions.

11:40.160 --> 11:47.320
The two concessions most frequently spoken of are to put a $750 million limit on the

