Thank you very much.

15:00.680 --> 15:03.560
Ladies and gentlemen friends with Tennessee.

15:03.560 --> 15:08.240
One of the most important discussions taking place in Washington these days is the matter

15:08.240 --> 15:12.720
that has not come to the floor of the Senate and the former than its village yet.

15:12.720 --> 15:16.760
This discussion that I have in mind is taking place largely before the Senate's finance

15:16.760 --> 15:20.800
committee and it involves the tight money policy.

15:20.800 --> 15:25.800
This policy is being descended by the second care of the Treasury, Comfort, who is widely

15:25.800 --> 15:29.760
recognized as a man who knows money and money policies.

15:29.760 --> 15:34.640
It is being attacked by Senator Bob Kerr of Oklahoma and others who are just as well recognized

15:34.640 --> 15:36.880
for the same quality.

15:36.880 --> 15:39.920
You have all heard of the laws that fly in demand.

15:39.920 --> 15:45.420
The tight money policy is a device employed by the administration which is designed to

15:45.420 --> 15:51.000
bring down the man down to the level of the class by restricting the ability of business

15:51.000 --> 15:54.800
and individuals to borrow money or to obtain credit.

15:54.800 --> 15:56.800
It is opposed to eliminate inflation.

15:57.440 --> 16:02.080
Well I'm no financial expert but my mother used to tell me that the proof of the pudding

16:02.080 --> 16:03.080
is in the eating.

16:03.080 --> 16:09.000
It seems to me that the proof of the failure of the tight money policy to control inflation

16:09.000 --> 16:13.120
is in the inflation that we are experiencing at the present time.

16:13.120 --> 16:18.400
Since this new policy was adopted over a year and a half ago, living costs have continued

16:18.400 --> 16:23.800
to hit new highs each month or 14 months out of the last 15.

16:23.800 --> 16:28.360
We don't have to look at fancy charts to note that we are having inflation.

16:28.360 --> 16:34.160
Most of us can simply tell by looking into our wallet and into our firsts.

16:34.160 --> 16:38.680
I have my wallet here and I know that I can tell that we are having inflation every

16:38.680 --> 16:43.400
time Nancy returns from a trip to the grocery store.

16:43.400 --> 16:46.800
Why has this policy failed to check inflation?

16:46.800 --> 16:50.920
Very simply because I think we are having a different kind of inflation.

16:50.920 --> 16:56.680
The kind of inflation that tight money policy might cure would be the kind we had during

16:56.680 --> 17:02.000
the war when we had the limited things that people could buy and we had the OTA and the OCS

17:02.000 --> 17:03.000
for that purpose.

17:03.000 --> 17:07.200
And it is the wrong remedy for the other kind of inflation.

17:07.200 --> 17:11.080
You don't have to be an expert to know that something is wrong and prices continue to

17:11.080 --> 17:17.720
go up in industries where production is falling and where goods are and over supply.

17:17.720 --> 17:22.320
As an example, the steel industry last week announced that it was raising the price of

17:22.320 --> 17:28.600
steel $6 a ton and yet we know the figures released by the industry itself that it is

17:28.600 --> 17:32.480
operating nearly 20% below its full capacity.

17:32.480 --> 17:36.920
So we can see that it isn't the law to plan the man that is responsible for increasing

17:36.920 --> 17:39.000
prices of steel.

17:39.000 --> 17:42.880
But what is happening is just the opposite of what you would expect.

17:42.880 --> 17:44.680
What then is responsible?

17:44.680 --> 17:49.480
I think that the answer is simply that some concentrated industries have the power to

17:49.480 --> 17:55.840
raise prices even when demand is falling and do not hesitate to exercise that power.

17:55.840 --> 17:59.480
Steel is just one such concentrated industry.

17:59.480 --> 18:05.000
The overall effectiveness phenomena is an increasing in the cost of living in the face of a falling

18:05.000 --> 18:07.440
demand for their products.

18:07.440 --> 18:13.200
This is a type of inflation which can be only minutely affected by a tight money policy.

18:13.200 --> 18:17.280
It is somewhat like taking an aspirin to cure a penicillin.

18:17.280 --> 18:22.000
If the tight money policy was of any substantial benefit in holding the type of inflation we

18:22.000 --> 18:26.240
have today, you can be sure that I would be all-farring.

18:26.240 --> 18:32.000
But not only is it the wrong remedy, it also has many and jury side effects of its own.

18:32.000 --> 18:37.000
It hurts small business badly, but they are the first to be cut off from the supply of

18:37.000 --> 18:38.000
credit.

18:38.000 --> 18:42.880
Even if they can obtain enough credit, the interest rates will take so high that the cost of loans

18:42.880 --> 18:45.600
become an unbearable burden.

18:45.600 --> 18:51.600
In addition, a tight money prevents much needed construction such as homes, highways, schools

18:51.600 --> 18:53.520
and things of that sort.

18:53.520 --> 18:57.800
It creates high interest rates that are often passed on to the consumers.

18:57.800 --> 19:02.480
It even forces the government to pay much higher rates for the money it times necessary

19:02.480 --> 19:05.640
as a bar and thus increases tax.

19:05.640 --> 19:09.480
So the poor consumer gets stuck with the bill no matter which way he turns.

19:09.480 --> 19:13.800
The Senate Finance Committee and its present hearings is trying to come up with a new

19:13.800 --> 19:14.800
description.

19:14.800 --> 19:19.800
And this week the Subcommittee on Antitrust and Monopoly in which I am chairman is going

19:19.800 --> 19:25.640
to begin a separate inquiry into those industries which maintain administered prices, posted

19:25.640 --> 19:30.320
prices at which they will sell regardless of the fluctuation of the man.

19:30.320 --> 19:34.680
We must know more about the effects of such industries before we can describe the remedy.

19:34.680 --> 19:39.640
There is no doubt that the patient shows signs of illness, the tight money policy described

19:39.640 --> 19:43.000
as sedative, which has yet to prove its value.

19:43.000 --> 19:47.920
But we need is complete and thorough diagnosis to determine the cause of the disease.

19:47.920 --> 19:50.080
Then we will be able to keep the patient recording.

19:50.080 --> 20:03.400
Thank you and goodbye until next week.

